TSP

Introduction

  • The origins of the travelling salesman problem are unclear. A handbook for travelling salesmen from 1832 mentions the problem and includes example tours through Germany and Switzerland, but contains no mathematical treatment.
  • The travelling salesman problem was mathematically formulated in the 1800s by the Irish mathematician W. R. Hamilton and by the British mathematician Thomas Kirkman.
  • Hassler Whitney at Princeton University introduced the name travelling salesman problem soon after.
  • Selmer M. Johnson expressed the problem as an integer linear program and developed the cutting plane method for its solution.
  • Richard M. Karp showed in 1972 that the Hamiltonian cycle problem was NP-complete, which implies the NP-hardness of TSP.
  • Great progress was made in the late 1970s and 1980.

Problem Definition

Given a list of cities and the distances between each pair of cities, what is the shortest possible route that visits each city exactly once and returns to the origin city?

Brute Force

  • Consider all the possible solutions, n! possible solutions
  • only tractable for n = 12, 13

Heuristics

Greedy Method

Nearest Neighbor

  • Quite similar to Prim’s MST algorithm

  • Simplest and most straightforward TSP heuristic

  • The Nearest Neighbor algorithm will often keep its tours within 25% of the Held-Karp lower bound

Greedy

  • Quite similar to Kruskal’s MST algorithm

  • constructs a tour by repeatedly selecting the shortest edge and adding it to the tour when:

    • doesn’t create a cycle with less than n edges
    • doesn’t increases the degree of any node to more than 2

  • The Greedy algorithm normally keeps within 15-20% of the Held-Karp lower bound

    • Tour Improvement

    2-opt

    • removes two edges from the tour, and reconnects the two paths created.
    • Continue removing and reconnecting the tour until no 2-opt improvements can be found.
    • Running the 2-opt heuristic will often result in a tour with a length less than 5% above the Held-Karp bound

    3-opt

    • 3-opt algorithm works in a similar fashion to 2-opt algorithm
    • The improvements of a 3-opt heuristic will usually give us a tour about 3% above the Held-Karp bound

    Practical Implementation

    1. Using Nearest Neighbor algorithm to construct an initial tour
    2. Then using 2-opt strategy to improve the initial tour
    3. Running the 1 and 2 100 times
    4. Selecting the best result from the 100 above results
